deck_name: The Winged Dragon of Ra OTK (Genesys)
deck_description: a deck totally focused on going second

Ghoti has been a fan favorite of many people since release, including me, however, it has never had the chance to actually be meta relevant. Well, this changes now, in the lower power format that is Genesys the fish migth actually be good enough. Not only is the base deck 0 points, with the only mandatory card that costs anything being Dragite, but taking advantage that not many handtraps fill the format by going all out and being able to play some of the best handtraps themselves.

This version of the deck is better going second, but the side deck has some blowout that can win the game if you want to go first in games 2 and 3. More specifically the interaction between Stealh Kragen and Virtue Stream. Depending on the deck your facing that by it self can win the game.

Tested deck in-house tournaments with up to 16 players. It was tested in over 5 of these and performed incredibly well, consistently ranking in the top 4 each time. Have fun with it. I'm not sure if I want to play 3 Awakening Forests, so I'd love some input. The math says I don't need it, but I love seeing the card. 

Siding:

Revival golem and Gravekeepers trap are sided in going first for the two pankertops.

Aluber the Jester of Despia searches for Despia, Theater of the Branded. Theater of the Branded can fusion summon a level 8 or higher fusion monster by using the monsters in your hand or field as material.

Aluber + any light or dark Shaddoll monster = Masquerade the Blazing Dragon or Despian Quaeritis

Like Theater of the Branded, Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous can fusion summon a level 8 or higher fusion monster by using the monsters in your hand or field as material.

Blazing Cartesia + any Shaddoll monster = El Shaddoll Construct

Blazing Cartesia + any light or dark Shaddoll monster = Granguignol the Dusk Dragon

Granguignol can send El Shaddoll Apkallone from the extra deck to the graveyard to search for or recover a Shaddoll card, then discard 1 card.

deck_excerpt: Gotta catch 'em all! Legendaries at least!
deck_description:
I will refer to each as their pokemon counterpart only, not sorry. 

Kyoro = Groudon | Kairo = Kyogre | Genro = Rayquaza | Tensei = Giratina | Sosei = Arceus

- The moment you get Arceus, Melody, or Rising in your hand, you're basically set to board spam everything, assuming your opponent cannot stop you.
- Remember that the full potential of War Zone is only when Arceus is faced up on top of the extra deck to get everything rolling.
- Giratina is a stupid card to have in your pendulum zone negating anything that would touch your Pokemon spells. 
- Kyogre will continuously be dumped into the grave, Rayquaza will be chillin in the banished pile, and Groudon will be abused between the deck and your cand constantly. 
- Varudras is your ultimate ace in the hole against anything dumb coming your way. 
- The continuous spells are indeed useful when needed, but remember when to sack any of your pokemon cards for them. 
- Super Poly is self-explanatory, board-breaking little pest it is. 
- Superdreadnoughts are literally an OHKO if you get the combo off
- Assortment of fusions I found useful while playing the deck for Super Poly fodder, change them as you see fit! 
- Fuwalos can be swapped for Maxx C, I just don't have one IRL to utilize to the fullest. 

Hope you enjoy a pure pokemon deck! Other fun ways to incorporate them are a DInomorphia/Pokemon split with them, or a Jurrac/Pokemon Stun deck.

deck_excerpt: Goblin Bikers deck for Rivalry of Warlords 2025 format.
deck_description: Goblin Bikers deck for Rivalry of Warlords 2025 format.

Trying out the new Genesys format with and old favorite.

The jank of the jank lives and breathes in my veins and I'm here to give it to you.

Wanna make Cyberdark End go "brrrr"? well you can do that. That's the standard combo for the deck.

Alternatively you can go into a XYZ combo and grab out your Infinity and King Regulus for a double omni-negate setup.

You can also go through a small Nova/Infinity combo into Stardust Synchron to cheat away 5 cards from the top of your deck with Chaos Ruler and then turn him into Shooting Majestic Star for a second approach at a double omni-negate setup.

Bust some boards with Eltanin or Clockwok Night.

Nearly every combo in this deck is searchable through 4 different starters (Core, Claw, Emergency, Horizon).


This deck is designed to go First or Second. Though preferrably First with the majority of the combo power relying on setting up a "nope" board.

Play the classic Cyber Dragon archetype with a new spin to it's internal struucture.

deck_excerpt: A opportunity to test the possibilities capable with the Killer Tune engine.
deck_description:
Synopsys: A Killer Tune focused deck that utalizes a Psychic engine to support it's first turn plays, with PSY-Frame and Brain Controller to help boost it's going secound capability.

Main Line Combo:

Combo: "Killer Tune Cue"

(Going First: Normal Line)

  • {Only If you start with "Synchro Overtake"}
    • Use "Synchro Overtake" to SS "K.Tune Mix"
    • "K.Tune Mix" effect to Search "K.Tune Cue"
  • NS "K.Tune Cue" Use it's on summon abbility to SS "Red Nova"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Track" using "K.Tune Cue" + "Red Nova"
    • CL1: "K.Tune Track" CL2: "Red Nova" CL3: "K.Tune Cue"
      • Resolve CL3:  how ever you wish
      • Resolve CL2: SS "K.Tune Reco"
      • Resolve CL1: Search "Juke Joint"
  • On Summon effect of "K.Tune Reco" Search "K.Tune Clip"
  • Place "Juke Joint" on field and activate "Juke Joint" effect
    • Send "K.Tune Track" and then SS "K.Tune Mix"
      • (If you started the line with "Syncro Overtake" Send "K.Tune Track" To SS "K.Tune Cue" instead Then Ignore the next bullet point)
    • "K.Tune Mix" effect Search "K.Tune Cue"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Remix" using "K.Tune Mix" + "K.Tune Cue"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Red Seal" using "K.Tune Reco" + "K.Tune Clip"

Synopsis: This is the line that you will most likely be going into a majority of the time. It ends on multiple interactions as well as follow up for the next turn. This line also leaves you with an extra normal summon off of "Juke Joint" so if you were to draw Mind Procedure or Brain Controller you can use them as extenders to either set up more disruption on you're opponents turn or breakers for your next turn.

(Going First: Normal Line + Mind Procedure)

  • Do the Normal Line to completion without using "Juke Joint" secound NS.
    • NS "Mind Procedure" use effect to Search "Teleport Fusion"
    • Set "Teleport Fusion"
  • End Turn

(Opponents Turn)

  • At the most opertune time activate "K.Tune Remix" Target "K.Tune Mix" + "K.Tune Clip"
    • Add "K.Tune Clip" to hand then SS "K.Tune Mix"
    • Synchro summon "Silent PSY Magician" using "Mind Procedure" + "K.Tune Mix"
  • Activate "K.Tune Clip" To SS itself the Syncro Summon
  • Syncro Summon "Shooting Riser Dragon" using "Silent PSY Magician" + "K.Tune Clip"
    • CL1:"K.Tune Clip" CH2:"Shooting Riser Dragon CL3: "Teleport Fusion"
      • Resolve CL3: SS "Axon Kicker Oracle"
      • Resolve CL2:  Reccomend you Send "Mind Controller" or "Effect Veiler" to the grave from deck but you can send any lvl you want depending on what you whish to end on.
        • You can also chose not to activate "Shooting Riser Dragon" if you wish to Synchro into Level 10's instead
      • Resolve CL1: Banish from Extra deck
  • On banish activation of "Mine Procedure" to SS itself to field
  • Activate "Shooting Riser Dragon"  to Synchro Summon the monster based what you chose to mill with "Shooting Riser Dragon" using "Shooting Riser Dragon" + "Mine Procedure" (Not all cards included in deck list just options that you can go into) 
    • lv7: "F.A Dawn Dragster", "Black Rose Dragon/Moonlight", "Clear Wing", "PSY - Framelord Zeta"
    • lv8: "Accel Synchro", "Crystal Wing", "Berserker of the Tenyi", " PSY - Framelord Omega"
    • lv9: "VW - Shenshen", "Navy Dragon Mech", 
    • lv10: "Chaos Angle", "Chengying", "Shooting Star Dragon"

Synopsis:This line is allows for more felxability with your Endboard and extradeck. Depending on how you choose to build your extra deck you have a multitude of ways to fill in any holes that you might find with your end board. The main down side this has is that if you wish to shotgun the end board you will lose on some interactions that you could have goten from your Killer Tune Cards. 

(Going Secound: Brain Control Line)

  • NS "K.Tune Cue" Use it's on summon abbility to SS "Brain Controller"
    • On Summon use "Brain Controller" to search "Brain Control"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Track" using "K.Tune Cue" + "Brain Controller"
    • CL1: "K.Tune Track" CL2: "K.Tune Cue" CL3: "Brain Controller
      • Resolve: CL2 and CL3 how ever you wish
      • Resolve: CL1 "K.Tune Track" Search"Juke Joint"
  • Place "Juke Joint" on field and activate "Juke Joint" effect
    • Send "K.Tune Track" Summon "K.Tune Mix" 
    • "K.Tune Mix" effect Search "K.Tune Reco"
    • NS "K.Tune Reco" Search "K.Tune Clip"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Red Seal" Using "K.Tune Mix" + "K.Tune Reco"

Synopsis: This line is better going secound as you keep all the main interactions that you would have if you did the Red Nova line but also get to add Brain Control to take an opponents monster. This line also incentives going into early "K.Tune Loudness War" To gain the Attack Bonus off the field spell as Brain Controller gets summoned to the opponents field if used for a synchro summon.

This line can also be used for going first if as in exchange for the extra Distruption that you would get through the "Red Nova" line by summoning "Brain Controller" on the opponents field you now have protection against board breakers like; "Infinite Impermance", "Lightning Storm" and "Evenly Matched" and even the prevent your opponent from using the "Mulcahrmys" during their turn.

 

Pros and Cons

(Pro's)

  • The Deck has a Lot of room for HandTraps/non engine
  • Can play very low to the ground through hand traps and board breakers
  • "Brain Control" gives going secound a searchable Board Breaker.
  • "Mind Procedure" allows for a higher cealing and flexability on what the deck can accomplish
  •  A lot of the lines have built in Chain Blocking so you don't need to wory about certain hand traps.
  • Can use Hand traps as both Interuption and as extenders making duplicate draws less frustrating
  • Turn Zero plays

(Con's)

  • Weak to all of the Mulcharmy's as the deck SS from Hand, Deck and Grave multiple times on both turns make it so that they are always online.
  • "Mind Procedure" Lines are slow and easy to disrupt
  • If you dont have access to NS "K.Tune Cue" or if they prevent the SS you're end board is signifigantly weaker
  • The Tuner lock while not detrimental to the game plan dose limit you're synergies and going first plays.
  • dose not have a way to counter Nibiru before the 5th summon
  • Cannot use and is suseptible to the Dominus traps
  • Engine dose not have a consistent way to search it's in archtype trap and quick play without hard drawing them.

Conclusion

Overall Killer Tune is a strong deck with a cohesive game plan that allows it to play going first or secound with little issues. It's ability to use Hand Traps both as disruption and as extenders makes them always playable even if their activation conditons are unavailable. The inherent locks in the deck do limit what engines you can use but can be easly cirumvented and the ability to play low to the ground makes it so that your never in a situation where you're not playing. But it dose have a hard time playing into or arround alot of the current best HandTraps: Mulcharmy's, Nibiru and the Dominus Traps give the deck very clear choke points that can be exploited.

deck_excerpt: Phryxul is the perfect missing link to combine Branded and Dracotail!
deck_description:
Phryxul is the perfect card to bridge both Branded and Dracotail decks! Before Phryxul's release from DOOD, the Branded Dracotail player would be forced instead to go to Lubellion by sending Mululu and Albaz, which may search a Dracotail spell/trap, but neglects searching for a Branded spell/trap because of the lack of Albion. Forget Phryxul's effects for a second, her most important characteristic is her attribute - LIGHT! This allows Branded Fusion to fusion summon Albion using Phyxul and Albaz, allowing you to simultanously search a Dracotail spell/trap and a Branded spell/trap during the End Phase (aka Main Phase 3 for Branded players)!

As a result, Branded Dracotail is now a much more synergistic fusion of both archetypes! This strategy generates a ton of massive beatsticks on field, smashes through established boards with in-engine cards, and generates a ton of advantage! Albax and Phryxul has truly made the ultimate fusion strategy!

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: This deck takes advantage of the lower power format of Genesys to play a full-power Shining Sarcophagus deck.
deck_description:
This deck takes advantage of the lower power format of Genesys to play a full-power Shining Sarcophagus deck. 
The deck prioritizes getting the main card, Sarcophagus, on the field. If you open no Sarcophagus or Gadget Trio, but have Dark Magician Girl or Future Silence, resolve these so you can special summon Dark Magician Girl. Then you can play Shining Sarcophagus. From there, you summon Dark Magician of Destruction to search your Dark Magician. This gives a consistent line for using your Dragon's Mind.
The Pot of Greed and Upstart Goblin allow the deck to run at 35 cards with 12 starters. Shining's greatest weakness is not getting enough starters in your opening hand. (You need about 1 per negate your opponent has on resolution.)


Other Tips: Keep Super poly in your hand if you go first, and have a good opening, then use it during your own next draw phase to out there board if they comboed off.


Cards to replace: (These are the weakest cards in the deck and ones I'm considering removing for something else)
     Quaking Mirror Force (Powerful when combined with Gandora, but very slow)
     Widow Anchor (Only works if you have no field)
     Angel Statue (Predictable and adds very little value if you go 2nd or don't draw it in your opening hand)
     2nd Gandora (The deck only needs one, but 2nd does come up sometimes for fusions and discard fodder)

deck_excerpt: Blue eyes genesys primite Blue-Eyes genesys format
Infamous ritual archetypes join forces in this powerful combo deck with control tendencies
deck_description:
This deck uses the power of generic ritual cards, such as the Impcantations, the "Rites" spells, as well as ASHLAN U1000, a recent TCG exclusive Link 2. It requires 2 monsters with different types and attributes, and says once per turn (hopt) you can reveal 1 Ritual Monster in your hand; add, from your deck to your hand, 1 Ritual Monster with a different Type and Attribute.

So this means that you can do the following: normal summon Gishki Grimness, special summon Gishki Abyss from deck, add Gishki Vision from deck to hand, discard vision to add Evigishki Neremanas from deck to hand, then link summon Salamangreat Almiraj using gishki grimness (600 ATK), then link summon ASHLAN U1000 using Almiraj and Gishki Abyss. From here, simply reveal Neremanas to add Ame no Habakuri no Mitsurugi from deck to hand.

The doorways ASHLAN U1000 opens up from a deckbuilding perspective for Ritual decks is really mindblowing. Here we have a link 2 that can be summoned in almost any ritual deck, and thrives off the combination of different archetypes due to their inherently different typing and attributes.

The impcantations offer surprising flexibility. Take Impcantation Chalislime, a card that mimics Habakuri's special ability that lets you reveal itself to summon a monster that tutors another card. It can now be used as a one-card combo enable due to the fact that it can summon talismandra, letting you directly add Habakuri from deck to hand. Evigishki Gustkraken is your main target when using the Impcantation Inception, the archetypes built in ritual spell. The impcantations ability to set up 2 successive ritual summons with any level 6 or lower ritual monster works perfectly with Gustkraken, easily allowing you to rip 2 cards from the opponents hand before/after almost any section of this combo. From there, you can overlay into an M7 to retrieve any monster from the graveyard, including any monster discarded by chalislime to activate its effect in the first place.

To be able to use a a ritual package like the impcantations but then also have the ability to bypass their use if necessary is absurd, and with 20 one card starters, only 7 of them actually requiring your normal summon, the deck features excellent flexibilty and starting power. The mitsurugi engine turns each chalislime, preparation of rites, focused aquamirror or gishki grimness into Mitsurugi Habakuri access, a strong upside to the investment.

None of this would matter if we didn't have an ace in the hole, a way to bottleneck all incoming decks from defeating your board. Mitsurugi already produced flexible, deep end boards that could navigate around opponents interruption. Now, with the addition of ASHLAN U1000 into almost every combo situation, we now have a way to consistently summon Spright Sprind. This lets us send Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier from deck to graveyard, conveniently setting up a Rank 2 summon of Gigantic Spright using Spright Sprind and Mirror Mage. This of course gives you access to your Gishki Grimness from the deck, but it also gives you access to another important Level 2 Monster: Knightmare Corruptor Iblee.

By linking Gigantic Spright and Iblee into an I:P Masquerana, and making sure all of your monsters are in defense position, you are now able to lock down the opponents board. The opponent will 99.99% of the time will try to normal summon a monster in order to link it and Iblee away to unlock their board. When they do this, you just link IP and a ritual monster (most often will be Mitama as per normal Mitsurugi end boards) into Dyna Mondo to shuffle whatever monster they have. If they move to battle phase to attack Dyna Mondo and finally break the lock, simply activate Dyna Mondo to re-summon Mitama (or any other ritual) from the GY in defense position, ruining their chances of getting rid of Iblee and moving their turn to Main Phase 2, guarunteeing that you get to go to the next turn!

This build of deck is the next generation of Mitsurugi Ritual Hybrids. Feel free to improve this concept. Enjoy!

Just a Dark World deck on full XYZ support.

Quick-synchro on your opponent's turn!

Going first:

  1. N.S. Rescue Cat or Nimble Beaver to go into Melffy of the Forest
  2. Search out Melffy Wally
  3. Melffy Wally effect in the end phase
  4. Opponent's turn: Melffy Catty + Melffy Puppy effects
  5. Search Melffy Pinny and summon Kalantosa
  6. Pop a card and then synchro summon into Desert Locusts with Pinny
  7. Desert Locust rip a card out of the hand
  8. Desrer Locusts can quick synchro into an 8 of your choice

Mannequin Cat:

  • Jinzo for Dark
  • Retaliating "C" for Earth
  • Ghost Ogre or Noble Arms Shield-Bearer for light
    • Ghost Ogre can also be used from the field
    • Shield-Bearer can draw a card if you had a light in your graveyard previously (ie: Veiler or Ogre)
  • Kaijus can trigger Mannequin Cat (hence the Earth and Dark Kaijus)

Going second:

  • Retaliating "C" or Rescue-Ace Impulse can trigger to summon out a body during the opponent's turn
  • Hop-Ear Squadron to quick synchro and interrupt your opponent
    • Retaliating "C" can search out Maxx "C" here
  • Kaiju a monster, summon Alpha and bounce back the Kaiju if you want to use it again
  • Ronnin Raccoon to make big token and punch over stuff if you need

deck_excerpt: Truly seize the power of DoomZ by making use of several power XYZ support cards, including Surfacing Big Jaws and Seventh Tachyon
deck_description:
Thought I'd share my take on the deck.

Running all the DoomZ cards for consistency.

Medius and his associated spells because he's the best starter and getting to him is really strong.

Seventh Tachyon + Big Jaws lets you access basically the whole deck. Number 102 searches Medius, Number 101 searches Big Jaws and number 107 searches Drastea. You can really fill any holes in your opening hand by just searching whatever you're missing so I feel running the targets in extra is a small price to pay, especially when atleast 101 is useful for board breaking.

Because of Big Jaws + Shark Drake you also have access to XYZ that need 3 monsters as material. I chose the Dark Matter Demolition line because its the easiest to get going, but you could just as easily make Shark Drake LeVeiss if you're able to search an equip, which is slightly better to me because it OTKs easier, the monster negate works anywhere and it has good stats to stick around.

All in all I feel this strikes a good balance of consistency and power, although droll does hurt a bit if you don't have extension.
